Hi there,

Welcome to the...

🎥 Biggest, Baddest B-roll Update! 🎉

And is it a firestorm! This month's update is packed with 10
blazing new features that are going to blow you away:

1. More B-rolls ⭐

B-roll so good its the A-roll. 😉 Now you can crank the frequency
slider to max, and we’ll fully cover your sequence in B-rolls.
Perfect for “faceless” videos!

2. Transitions 🎞️

Let it flow with Premiere Pro native transitions added directly
by FireCut. No more jump cuts! You can even adjust the duration
to get the ideal outcome.

3. More scaling options 🖼️

Get the perfect fit with our new scale setting. Want to take up
the full frame? → "Scale to Fill". Or if you prefer a frame
around the edges? → "Scale to Fit"

4. Bring on the GIFs 👾

If you follow us on our instagram (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/xmuedd8zxdi6hppkq67a5h28xwlllin/wnh2hghq9wg8q9il/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuaW5zdGFncmFtLmNvbS9maXJlY3V0YXBwLw==
), you know we love our memes. 😁 And now so can you, as with this
upgrade you can add GIFs as B-rolls! How cool is that?! 😎

5. Not just GIFs... images too! 🏞️

And it doesn’t end there. You can also select multiple media
types (videos, images, GIFs) at once for a dynamic mix. 🎨

6. Easier editing options ✏️

Sometimes the first choice is not the right choice. And we get
that. Just click ‘Edit’ to browse and swap B-rolls anytime—even
after reopening Premiere Pro!

7. Credit the Creator 🏅

This update makes it effortless to acknowledge creators; get
attribution info (where available) for including in your video
descriptions to spread the love.

8. Full-Res, No Watermarks 🎥

If you find yourself clicking "Upgrade B-rolls" too often to
remove the Storyblocks watermark, you can use this setting to
skip this step altogether.

9. BYOB: Bring your own B-rolls 📸

So Mr. Nolan, you have your own stock library? No problem at all
because FireCut’s AI can search your library with reliability and
accuracy to find just the right clips that compliment your video.
👌

10. Bug Fixes 🐞

Always.

​

So, what are you waiting for? Give these updates a spin →
Download FireCut (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/xmuedd8zxdi6hppkq67a5h28xwlllin/reh8hohm90xnm2b6/aHR0cHM6Ly9maXJlY3V0LmFpL2Rvd25sb2Fkcy8=

column7: Price-reduction on serverless compute for Jobs, Pipelines and Notebooks extended
column9:
**

**

****

******

Dear Databricks Customer,

*We are reaching out to inform you that the limited-time 50% price reduction on serverless compute for Jobs, Pipelines (DLT), and 30% price reduction on Notebooks has been extended until April 30, 2025.*

*Pricing Update*
The following price reductions will continue to automatically apply to new and existing workloads using serverless compute, through April 30, 2025. These price reductions are reflected on your bill as an effective discount on the per DBU price of serverless compute. No action is required on your part; these reductions will apply on top of any other contractual discounts you may have.

* 50% price reduction on serverless compute for Jobs and Pipelines (DLT)
* 30% price reduction on serverless compute for Notebooks
* Prices will automatically revert to standard rates after April 30, 2025. Please view the following pricing pages for standard rates and additional details - Jobs ( https://www.databricks.com/product/pricing/jobs ) , Pipelines (DLT) ( https://www.databricks.com/product/pricing/delta-live ) , Notebooks ( https://www.databricks.com/product/pricing/datascience-ml ).

In addition to the extended price reductions, Databricks has recently announced the following capabilities to improve the price/performance of your serverless workloads:

* Efficiency improvements that help reduce the costs for short workloads ( https://www.databricks.com/blog/cost-savings-serverless-compute-notebooks-jobs-and-pipelines ).
* Cost observability ( https://docs.databricks.com/en/admin/system-tables/serverless-billing.html ) to help track and monitor spending at an individual Notebook, Job, and Pipeline level.
* Simple controls ( https://www.databricks.com/blog/cost-savings-serverless-compute-notebooks-jobs-and-pipelines ) for Jobs and Pipelines that will allow you to indicate a preference for optimizing workload execution based on cost rather than performance. (coming soon)

For more information, please visit the Databricks pricing page ( https://www.databricks.com/product/pricing ). If you have any questions, please contact your Databricks account team or reach us at help@databricks.com.

Thanks,
Databricks

column7: Why You're Stuck at Senior Data Engineer (And How to Break Out)
column9:
View this post on the web at https://seattledataguy.substack.com/p/why-youre-stuck-at-senior-data-engineer

So you've mastered Airflow, built hundreds of pipelines, and have racked up seven-plus years of experience, but you're still seen as just a Senior Engineer.
Maybe your title says “Lead,” but people come to you for tasks, not strategic insight. You’re the go-to for execution, not direction.
The reality? Technical skills only take you so far. At some point, most engineers hit what’s I’ve come to recognize as the senior plateau(although there is some term out there for it), and no, it’s not just you. Even with a supportive manager or director, pushing past it is hard. We keep thinking that if we just deliver more technical work, we’ll naturally level up.
In my experience? That’s not how it works.
Let’s talk about why many talented engineers get stuck at senior and how to break through it.
The Senior Plateau
At many enterprises and tech companies, senior is treated as a terminal role. You’re not really expected to grow much beyond that.
And for good reason, many data engineers are genuinely happy at that level. It’s a sweet spot between hands-on work and ownership, with just enough responsibility to stay interesting without getting pulled into politics.
In fact, I’ve met plenty of people whose goal was to reach senior and coast. No shame in that.
But for those who do want to break past the plateau, it’s easy to get stuck. This is where a lot of talented engineers stall out.
Here are a few signs you’ve hit the ceiling:
You get asked to execute, not influence [ https://substack.com/redirect/a9c95c89-1c09-4cc4-85e2-93d767bab363?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Promotions feel vague or out of reach
You’re seen as reliable, but not critical to strategy or decision-making
If you want to grow beyond senior, you can’t just keep relying on the skills that got you where you are. You’ll need to level up in a completely different way.
SeattleDataGuy’s Newsletter is a reader-supported publication. To receive new posts and support my work, consider becoming a free or paid subscriber.
The Skills That Got You Here Won’t Get You There
One of the biggest challenges senior engineers face is not knowing what to change. So they double down on what’s worked before:
Increasing technical output, more is more, right?
Learning horizontally, picking up new tools and frameworks
“I know Airflow [ https://substack.com/redirect/c869da2c-be66-459e-ac05-2deab3d49d30?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]; let me learn Mage [ https://substack.com/redirect/50fb1434-46dd-4bcc-8be5-da0ef59c4011?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] or perhaps MLFlow [ https://substack.com/redirect/a03594fa-5c19-43a8-b407-1d596eee8cde?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].”
“I am a good data engineer; maybe I should get into AI.”
“Let me build an even more complex system.”
The problem is you hit a limit in terms of how much it can grow your career. 
This is captured perfectly in Alex Ewerlöf  ’s illustration below. 
No one’s saying you should stop developing your technical skills. If you work in tech, you’ll always need to keep learning. But the career value those skills bring—if that’s your goal—starts to flatten after a certain point.
So, if you're trying to move beyond the senior plateau, here are some other areas to focus on.
Business Understanding is the Bridge
There’s a point where “doing more” just doesn’t scale. Early in your career, you were rewarded for high output. But over time, you realize that not every task is worth the time, and there’s only so much of it in the day. [ https://substack.com/redirect/ec959feb-ae34-4e98-92a7-c35600c67f7e?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
To figure out what is worth doing, you need to understand the business [ https://substack.com/redirect/5b8e8d1e-5892-4062-b4d9-7a22b55f4c11?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], both the industry and your company's current priorities.
Here are a few examples where technical work directly supports business impact:
Dev Experience: While most of us were writing MapReduce jobs, someone built Hive. Why? Because it sped up pipeline development and lowered the barrier for more people to work in data. It wasn’t a direct revenue driver, but it improved the company's ability to generate insights, ultimately enabling better, faster business decisions.
Inventory Optimization: Operations is over-ordering due to laggy sales reporting. You build a near real-time pipeline and dashboard [ https://substack.com/redirect/de0cd390-8cc5-4f10-a5f3-7cea93d8d802?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] that highlights slow-moving SKUs, reducing excess inventory by 25% in a single quarter.
Reducing Duplication: You notice multiple teams calculating churn in different ways. You create a canonical churn [ https://substack.com/redirect/2e70e669-5bbe-42cc-ab33-91901dfbcbaf?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] table and documentation that becomes the go-to resource, saving time and aligning insights across four departments.
To operate at this level, you’ll need more than strong code:
Prioritization
Communication with stakeholders
The ability to identify hidden opportunities
It also means you need to understand what truly drives your business, what many refer to as the levers.
Is the company focused on aggressive growth or profitability?
Are you competing for market share or trying to improve margins?
Is customer acquisition the challenge, or is retention the real issue?
The clearer you are on those levers, the better you can align your work and value with what matters most.
Your Ability to Take Calculated Risks
“When you have a strong enough worldview to lead, you’ll start to collect others around you who rely on you maintaining that world’s physics, and tolerating any deviation from your vision can feel like you’re letting them down.”
― Will Larson, Staff Engineer: Leadership Beyond the Management Track [ https://substack.com/redirect/7e5211a2-eedd-4692-a875-92f0f2c89d4f?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Part of growing past senior means stepping outside your comfort zone. It means taking everything you know about the business, and how data teams [ https://substack.com/redirect/76aaeeb4-b967-43dc-9d06-788b182b85cb?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] work, and using that context to offer suggestions and take more ownership/risk.
I want to highlight the risk part.
Earlier in your career, failure usually meant failing to ship a technical solution. Now, it’s broader. Failure could mean:
Picking the wrong project
Influencing in the wrong direction
Investing in something that doesn’t land
And that’s hard, because up until now, most of your success has come from doing things that you could control. Now, you’re dealing with ambiguity and outcomes that depend on others.
You might pitch an idea and get shot down.
You might lead a migration that people don’t adopt.
You might advocate for a tooling shift and realize later it wasn’t the real problem.
But taking smart risks, the kind based on context, relationships, and a real understanding of business impact [ https://substack.com/redirect/eff0781c-2c15-45e8-a398-abc6a24aaa67?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], is what separates those who stay at senior from those who move into Staff, Principal, or beyond.
Because at some point, it’s not just about what you can build. It’s about what you’re willing to bet on.
How to Break Through
If you’re still reading, it’s probably because you want more than just another promotion. You want to grow, take on bigger challenges, and become the kind of engineer who changes how a company works, not just how a pipeline runs.
But breaking through the senior plateau isn’t about waiting for someone to hand you a bigger title. It’s about changing how you operate.
Here are four concrete shifts that can help:
Build Context Proactively
You can’t make high-leverage decisions if you don’t understand the game being played. That means stepping outside your bubble and learning more than just what’s in your Jira queue.
Sit in on product planning meetings.
Shadow a stakeholder team for a sprint.
Ask how your company makes money and how it might lose it.
Engineers who understand business context build better systems. Period.
Share What You’re Thinking
You don’t get credit for good ideas that live only in your head.
Start writing. Start presenting. Start documenting your thinking, especially the tradeoffs behind decisions. This isn't just about personal branding. It’s about helping others follow your logic and trust your judgment.
Staff engineers aren’t just smart, they’re visible, thoughtful, and intentional.
Own Something Murky
Most senior engineers excel at delivering technical work. 
But the next level? That’s where you volunteer for the mess.
An initiative no one wants to own, but you believe you can deliver 
A data quality [ https://substack.com/redirect/ad1a62e3-2a7d-4a7c-ba20-846714fd3468?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] issue that crosses five teams
A migration [ https://substack.com/redirect/97cbe50a-0113-4f9d-81a6-1e459c531b48?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] with uncertain ROI
Staff+ engineers don’t wait to be assigned. They identify ambiguities, figure out the first step, and move.
Ask for (and Act on) Feedback
You might think you’re already operating at a Staff-level, but perception matters.
Ask your manager:
What’s missing between where I’m at and where I want to be?
Ask peers and cross-functional partners:
What’s one thing I could do to work better with you?
It takes humility, but that’s part of the leap. Growth at this level isn’t about adding more tools to your belt. It’s about sharpening your judgment, your communication, and your impact.
Final Thoughts
Making the jump from senior to staff isn’t easy, and every company defines it a little differently. But after talking with multiple leaders and working with dozens of clients, I’ve seen some consistent themes. The biggest one? Staff-level engineers drive impact independently. They don’t wait for a manager or director to steer the conversation. They lead it.
At many companies, Staff+ roles are treated as parallel to manager- or director-level roles in scope and influence. You're not just a better builder, you’re a strategic partner.
As the old saying goes: What got you here won’t get you there.
So be ready to learn new skills!
As always, thanks for reading.

The Data Leader’s Playbook Accelerator 
Over the past few years, I have led dozens of data team turnarounds, set up infrastructure for companies ranging from small start-ups to large billion-dollar organizations, and coached new data leaders on how to handle tough stakeholders.
Now, I wanted to condense all of that into a 6-week program that would help you be better prepared for dealing with issues such as:
Building trust with stakeholders
Picking the right tools while navigating aggressive sales tactics
Negotiating with vendors
Juggling ad-hoc business requests with long-term strategic planning
Dealing with a lot of hype around AI and real-time
Balancing their technical expertise while also having to lead
And more
Articles Worth Reading
There are thousands of new articles posted daily all over the web! I have spent a lot of time sifting through some of these articles as well as TechCrunch and companies tech blog and wanted to share some of my favorites!
Advancing Invoice Document Processing at Uber using GenAI
The traditional invoice processing approach relies on manual data entry or automation like RPA (Robotic Process Automation), Excel uploads, and rule-based systems. While Uber has automation solutions like RPA and self-serve supplier platforms, a significant portion of invoices still require manual handling. We believed that we could improve the existing process as the old process has proven inadequate in speed, accuracy, and cost-effectiveness.
To address ‌inefficiencies in ‌existing invoicing mechanisms, we implemented a GenAI-powered invoice automation system. This innovation uses advanced ML and NLP (Natural Language Processing) to automate and improve the invoice processing workflow, significantly reducing manual intervention and operational costs. The result is a robust and scalable system that accelerates invoicing processes, minimizes errors and improves the user experience.

2. You may also want to check out The Publish Press, a free newsletter by OG YouTubers Colin and Samir breaking down the business of creators three times a week. If you fancy joining over 130,000 creators getting the latest news, sign up here (https://djX7c204.eu1.hubspotlinks.com/Ctc/5H+113/djX7c204/VVBfZK8nskKLW7GHn0v24hnRBW7swsJQ5nGhXXN4WpFgb3pyd0W6N1vHY6lZ3nxW4CTHgc113mXJW1DfT0Q87kk8lW8Dt_wj2z5M24W1Vm5JX4MwTX4N4bbJZwjxTfpW1F-08z1TrhlZW4qVKDK6QZ3V2W3zzHmD556XLQW7T7z4J1NSmWfW8dKGRS918sVnV9zqtx84wMZlW94shB49drlQbVnc4Sv1sKrX0W5lfq6r5gn-5kW4SNdhW7PKB0fVNyQdt6zzm-tW25gZBN4CVllhW9k8v-h5wkf6sVtznRc2w4-bZW47RM9N6-t-ZRW501M-J5-bRC1W7X5Lbq2BZpgNf5z70k204 ) .

Anyway, let's talk about something I often get questions about - creativity. I had a minor epiphany about that recently that I'd love to share with you. Here's the story - this week, we published a YouTube video where I showed how I transformed my tiny room in Hong Kong into a glamorous studio (watch here (https://djX7c204.eu1.hubspotlinks.com/Ctc/5H+113/djX7c204/VVBfZK8nskKLW7GHn0v24hnRBW7swsJQ5nGhXXN4WpFgv3pyd0W7lCdLW6lZ3mkVm7ytl4tlt6PVtHbKQ8RNgq5W51YkX_3PLB3sVML47X5NZ4ldW2fG0nP8C04XKW3c3wxn9lwHCVW8_rWsZ4J86gyN2jL5D2kM0SHW3v64LV3DncylW8tNwSn2BYjDSN9cMltQB8sDqV1mkxQ6kc-7pW3Z_ldq87Qw-4W75hZg916FQnWW8jv46j64j6B6W5ZWLXF2kYDRVW6282Pj5PSkFlW3xN0Gt5PSQcDW11bKbv6WRdgtW823Vjd6hQjVwW4MW5GF1CqPyFN5zwkPBhPRp7W4H3vKx10y52YW6w-2Zc7D6XLCf68-lz404 ) if you fancy 😉).

At the start of the video, there was a transition shot where I snapped my fingers and the entire studio setup changed. It might just be one of my favorite things I've done in years.

The idea wasn't entirely "original". I first saw something similar in a Peter McKinnon video (https://djX7c204.eu1.hubspotlinks.com/Ctc/5H+113/djX7c204/VVBfZK8nskKLW7GHn0v24hnRBW7swsJQ5nGhXXN4WpFgv3pyd0W7lCdLW6lZ3mdW1pMGSG5TV7y7W8cdvmR4NQ-2YW3lLrf26cfDFsW5DQjnv7wV9S2VNVcT_7VBMwcV8XMyK36d8J3W8Wms_c1hfQ_VW5fjlJT2mrXb4W7PLDVZ3_d92bMF_WkVP6XyMW56z71N4hFBK2W6wD8mc1H9sRgW7ksTXK59HwjzW8k-g-F7Th5YwW8k1chs6FDjCmW8X5-lr24FMl1W6SXv8y8MyGBYW7KnLzR5bBS_qW60HtbB7XqdgYW6L3XC05XJ0SlW6pKFfd3yjsYBW4cCD1x2YnX8tW7rQPK288pQTPW4kWXBx3fjVYvf6NZKpF04 ) 7 years ago, where he used a finger-snap transition to show how to transform a terrible lighting situation into something amazing for less than $50.

Then about 4 years ago, I came across a tutorial about snap transitions on a random YouTube video. The real magic, I learned, was in the audio - you keep the echo of the snap going while the visual changes. That makes it feel way more realistic than just doing a straight cut.

I guess my subconscious mind stored these two events, from 7 and 4 years ago, to the point where when I was setting up my new studio, I thought "omg this is finally my chance to copy that snap transition". After filming and editing the opening, I excitedly showed a few friends, some of whom commented along the lines of "wow that's so creative".

That got me thinking - I never used to consider myself a creative person, because I felt I wasn't very original. But there's that quote from Steve Jobs: "Creativity is just connecting things".

The first bit of that quote is the "connecting" part. What looked like others to be "creative" in this case, was me connecting two YouTube videos I watched years ago, and applying it to my new living situation.

But the second bit of the quote is the "things" part. To connect things, you need to have things to connect. It sounds obvious, but I often speak to aspiring YouTubers who don't spend much time watching YouTube videos. Or increasingly to aspiring writers, who don't spend much time reading.

I've found that it's always worth "consuming" (urgh I hate that word) the "content" (I hate that word too) within the field you're creating in. I suspect Christopher Nolan probably spends a good chunk of time watching movies, for inspiration.

But of course, it's also good to consume content (urgh) outside of your own field. In every biography I've read, or every interview I've watched from any successful visionary creator or entrepreneur, they always have a bunch of eclectic interests outside of the field they work in. And they always credit those interests with a lot of their best ideas.

As a creator, you never really know which piece of content is going to be useful later. That tutorial you watch today might combine with a book you read next month to create something entirely new. It's all just background processing until something clicks.

In our Part-Time YouTuber Academy Q&As, students are often impressed when I can reference specific thumbnails or video styles from months ago. It's not because I have superhuman memory - it's just what happens when you enjoy the craft you’re doing, and enjoy seeing what others have created within it.

This is where the magic happens. That snap transition in the video is a combination of:

- A lighting technique from 6 years ago
- An audio trick from 4 years ago
- Various other bits and pieces I've picked up along the way

So here's what I'm thinking this week - if you're trying to make it as a creator, consuming content isn't just fun, it's part of the job. But don't just stick to your niche. Watch different types of content, read books, watch movies. Sometimes the best ideas come from unexpected places.

Have a great week!

Ali xx
